[15:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'really interesting point is that there\'s actually no AI generated images in their pre-training. They intentionally excluded AI generated images from their pre-training data because even a small'

[15:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'amount of synthetic data could bias the model\'s output. Their view is that synthetic images are easier for the model to learn, but they could damage quality and make the outputs feel more generic. And that\'s why the aesthetics'

[15:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of Creal 2 are so good. That\'s why their images look so realistic. It\'s because they haven\'t actually used any AI generated samples in their training data. Now, traditionally image models are rewarded during training if their'

[16:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'image outputs look good. In other words, if their aesthetics are good. However, if you aggressively filter for only beautiful, sharp, or clean images, then this might also introduce bias towards just polished or perfect images. Their'

[16:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'reasoning is that even a blurry or weird or a non-beautiful image still might be useful if the model understands exactly what it is. You shouldn\'t penalize the model for generating a weird or ugly image if it\'s still aligned with the'

[16:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'text prompt. They deployed a very rich captioning pipeline to create their data set. So, they took a bunch of images as the training data, and then they used OCR and metadata and long-form captions to teach the model what exactly is in'

[16:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'each image. They also reformat those captions into different lengths so the model can see different prompt styles. This matters because many people write prompts differently. Some people make it very descriptive. Some people like it'

[17:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'short and concise. And the model should be able to understand and handle all these different types of prompts. They were also very honest in discussing the limitations of scaling this further. So, they found that training became way less'

[17:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'stable if you scaled up the GPU count. So, running on 128 GPUs were very stable, but as they scaled up the GPU count, then it crashed a lot more frequently. In fact, they could not complete a single run at a very large'

[17:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'scale without a crash. So, this shows how much of Frontier image model training is not just about model architecture, it\'s not just about software or training data, but also debugging GPUs and NVLink and figuring out all this infrastructure stuff. A'

